Introduction¶

This notebook aims to classify images of Dogs vs Cats using two deep learning approaches:

1. A custom-built Convolutional Neural Network (CNN)¶

2. A fine-tuned VGG16 model pre-trained on ImageNet¶

¶

The goal is to explore the performance of both models on a reduced dataset (5000 images), analyze their strengths/limitations,¶

and gain practical experience in applying transfer learning.¶

Q2. EDA: Explore the Data¶

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import os
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Function to plot class distribution
def plot_class_distribution(directory, title):
    class_dirs = [cls for cls in os.listdir(directory) if cls != '.DS_Store']
    class_counts = {cls: len(os.listdir(os.path.join(directory, cls))) for cls in class_dirs}
    df = pd.DataFrame(list(class_counts.items()), columns=["Class", "Count"])
    sns.barplot(x="Class", y="Count", data=df)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.show()

Q3-a. Build and Train a Vanilla CNN Model¶

In [14]:
# Import necessary libraries for model building
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Conv2D, MaxPooling2D, Flatten, Dense, Dropout
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import ModelCheckpoint, EarlyStopping

# Define a simple CNN model
vanilla_model = Sequential([
    Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation='relu', input_shape=(150,150,3)),
    MaxPooling2D(2,2),
    Conv2D(64, (3,3), activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(2,2),
    Flatten(),
    Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    Dropout(0.5),
    Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
])

vanilla_model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

vanilla_cb = ModelCheckpoint("best_vanilla_model.h5", save_best_only=True, monitor="val_loss")
early_stop = EarlyStopping(patience=5)

history_vanilla = vanilla_model.fit(train_data, validation_data=val_data, epochs=15, callbacks=[vanilla_cb, early_stop])

Q3-b. Fine-Tune VGG16 Model¶

In [15]:
# import necessary libraries for plotting
from tensorflow.keras.applications import VGG16
from tensorflow.keras.models import Model
from tensorflow.keras.layers import GlobalAveragePooling2D

# Load VGG16 base model
base_model = VGG16(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=(150,150,3))

# Freeze base model layers
for layer in base_model.layers:
    layer.trainable = False

# Add custom layers
x = base_model.output
x = GlobalAveragePooling2D()(x)
x = Dense(128, activation='relu')(x)
x = Dropout(0.5)(x)
output = Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(x)

vgg_model = Model(inputs=base_model.input, outputs=output)

vgg_model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

vgg_cb = ModelCheckpoint("best_vgg_model.h5", save_best_only=True, monitor="val_loss")

history_vgg = vgg_model.fit(train_data, validation_data=val_data, epochs=10, callbacks=[vgg_cb, early_stop])

Plot Training Accuracy and Loss¶

In [16]:
# Function to plot accuracy and loss curves
def plot_metrics(history, title):
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,5))
    plt.subplot(1,2,1)
    plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'], label='train acc')
    plt.plot(history.history['val_accuracy'], label='val acc')
    plt.title(f'{title} Accuracy')
    plt.legend()
    plt.subplot(1,2,2)
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'], label='train loss')
    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'], label='val loss')
    plt.title(f'{title} Loss')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

plot_metrics(history_vanilla, "Vanilla CNN")
plot_metrics(history_vgg, "VGG16")

Q4. Evaluate and Compare Model Performance¶

In [17]:
# import necessary libraries for evaluation
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, confusion_matrix, ConfusionMatrixDisplay, precision_recall_curve
import numpy as np

# Load best weights
vanilla_model.load_weights("best_vanilla_model.h5")
vgg_model.load_weights("best_vgg_model.h5")

val_data.reset()
y_true = val_data.classes
y_pred_vanilla = (vanilla_model.predict(val_data) > 0.5).astype("int32")
y_pred_vgg = (vgg_model.predict(val_data) > 0.5).astype("int32")

# Function to evaluate and display confusion matrix
def evaluate_model(y_true, y_pred, model_name):
    print(f"\nClassification Report for {model_name}")
    print(classification_report(y_true, y_pred))
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred)
    ConfusionMatrixDisplay(cm, display_labels=['Cat','Dog']).plot()
    plt.title(f"{model_name} Confusion Matrix")
    plt.show()

evaluate_model(y_true, y_pred_vanilla, "Vanilla CNN")
evaluate_model(y_true, y_pred_vgg, "VGG16")

# Function to plot Precision-Recall curve
def plot_pr_curve(y_true, y_scores, model_name):
    precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_true, y_scores)
    plt.plot(recall, precision, marker='.')
    plt.title(f'{model_name} Precision-Recall Curve')
    plt.xlabel('Recall')
    plt.ylabel('Precision')
    plt.grid()
    plt.show()

val_data.reset()
y_scores_vgg = vgg_model.predict(val_data)
y_scores_vanilla = vanilla_model.predict(val_data)

plot_pr_curve(y_true, y_scores_vgg, "VGG16")
plot_pr_curve(y_true, y_scores_vanilla, "Vanilla CNN")

Q5. Conclusion¶

  • The tailored Vanilla CNN showed moderate performance but started to overfit early.
  • VGG16 utilizing transfer learning exhibited much better generalization and reached higher accuracy.
  • The confusion matrix and PR curves illustrate the superior performance of VGG16.
  • Misclassifications predominantly happened on unclear or ambiguous images.

¶

Transfer learning acts as an effective tool in image classification assignments, particularly when there is limited training data.
